message.content:
This command is used to establish an SSH (Secure Shell) tunnel between your local machine and a remote server, specifically the one hosted on Amazon Web Services (AWS) EC2 service at the address ec2-34-221-131-108.us-west-2.compute.amazonaws.com.

Let's break down the command:

- `ssh`: This is the SSH client, which allows you to connect to a remote server securely.
- `-i "~/UserKey.pem"`: This option specifies the path to your private key file (in this case, UserKey.pem) used for authentication with the remote server.
- `-C`: This option enables compression of the data being transferred which can help improve performance when dealing with larger amounts of data.
- `-L 25900:localhost:5900`: This is called local port forwarding, where it maps a local port (25900) on your machine to a remote address and port (localhost and 5900) on the server you're connecting to.
- `user@ec2-34-221-131-108.us-west-2.compute.amazonaws.com`: This is the address of the remote server you want to connect to, using the specified username (user).

After running this command and successfully connecting to the remote server, any connection made to your local machine's port 25900 will be forwarded to the remote server's port 5900. This can be useful for various purposes like accessing a remote desktop or application hosted on the server.
